  "analysis": "Input CSV has three columns with spaces and varying capitalization, separated by commas with spaces. Expected CSV has columns reversed order, uppercase, semicolon separators, and a fourth column 'OK' appended. Need to transform each line: 1) Trim spaces, 2) Reverse order of three fields, 3) Convert to uppercase, 4) Change delimiter from comma to semicolon, 5) Add ';OK' at end. Must do this for 1 million lines efficiently with Vim macros. Should create three macros: macro a maybe for cleaning spaces and reversing? Could use Vim normal mode commands like :s/^\\s*//, :s/\\s*$//, then reverse fields. However macros must be keystroke-efficient (<200 total). Let's examine more diff lines to confirm pattern.",
  "plan": "Check more diff lines to see if there are any other differences (maybe some lines have different content). Use diff with side-by-side view. Then design macros. Possibly macro a: delete leading spaces and trailing spaces, convert commas to semicolons, uppercase? But uppercase transformation needed: we can use :s/\\w/\\U&/g. Might need to split into steps. We'll write a Vim macro using normal mode commands that can be recorded and then set via setreg. Let's test interactively in Vim to see what keystrokes work. We'll create a temporary test file and record macro, then extract keystrokes. Use vim -u NONE to test.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /app\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cp input.csv test.csv\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "vim -Nu NONE -n test.csv\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Vim opened test.csv with first lines displayed. Need to design macros. Let's first exit Vim to plan. Press ESC and :q!.",
  "plan": "Exit Vim, then write a small script to test transformation using Vim commands. We'll create a macro that does the following on a single line: 1) Remove leading/trailing spaces (maybe using :s/^\\s*// and :s/\\s*$//). 2) Replace commas with semicolons. 3) Reverse order of three fields. Could be done via regex capturing groups. Let's examine pattern: fields are separated by comma with optional spaces. Could do :s/^\\(.*\\)\\s*,\\s*\\(.*\\)\\s*,\\s*\\(.*\\)$/\\U\\3;\\U\\2;\\U\\1;OK/. Need to uppercase each field. Use \\U\\3 etc. However uppercase conversion will affect only the captured group? In Vim, \\U turns uppercase until \\E. So we can do :s/^\\(.*\\)\\s*,\\s*\\(.*\\)\\s*,\\s*\\(.*\\)$/\\U\\3;\\U\\2;\\U\\1;OK/. Need to also trim spaces inside fields? The spaces inside fields are part of the captured group and will be uppercased but spaces stay. However fields may have internal spaces? Looking at input: fields are like 'alpha1' with no internal spaces. So spaces are only around commas. So captured groups include leading/trailing spaces? Actually pattern includes \\s* before and after comma, but captured groups are (.*) which may include spaces before/after because .* is greedy and will match spaces before the next separator? Let's test with a small file using vim -c. We'll write a test script and run.",
